# ADR-003: Initial project scope will focus on controlled v1 definition before solver implementation

- Date: 2026-04-15
- Status: accepted
- Deciders: Director
- Technical area: product scope

## Context

The long-term ambition of the project is broad: an open-source YAML-based server-client modeling platform for loudspeaker simulation with LEM and BEM capabilities. However, beginning implementation before freezing a narrow v1 scope would increase drift, waste budget, and make AI task packets too ambiguous.

ADR practice recommends separating phased decisions instead of collapsing short-term and long-term approaches into one record. [web:39]

## Decision

The project will not begin solver implementation until the v1 scope is explicitly defined in repository documents.

The next planning focus will define:
- target user problems,
- v1 use cases,
- v1 non-goals,
- first benchmark cases,
- first deliverables,
- phase boundaries for early development.

The likely initial domain is horn and waveguide related loudspeaker problems, but the exact v1 scope remains to be formalized in the next planning phase.

## Consequences

Benefits:
- Prevents premature coding.
- Improves task packet quality.
- Keeps costs under control by reducing exploratory implementation churn.
- Makes audits meaningful.

Costs:
- Delays coding start slightly.
- Requires up-front planning effort.

Trade-off:
The project accepts a slower start in exchange for a cleaner and cheaper development trajectory.

## Alternatives considered

- Alternative 1: start coding a generic solver core immediately.
- Alternative 2: prototype many unrelated solver directions in parallel.
- Alternative 3: rely on evolving chat discussions instead of formal v1 definition.

## Supersession

None.
